The Wide-field Infrared Survey Explorer \citep[WISE,][]{WISE2010} was a mission funded by NASA that mapped the whole sky at mid-IR wavelengths from December 2009 to February 2011. It had a much better sensitivity than that of earlier IR survey missions. The different survey bands and resolutions are shown in Table~\ref{Tab:WISE_Survey}.

Bow shocks are related to the warm dust emission, and this emission is mostly expected in the W4 band. Therefore, we used the W4 band to look for bow shock or bubble-like structures around the runaway stars. WISE images are available through the WISE Image Service\footnote{\href{https://irsa.ipac.caltech.edu/applications/wise/}{irsa.ipac.caltech.edu/applications/wise/}} of the NASA/IPAC Infrared Science Archive.

